#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:9 82e688d691c848d6b42d786861111c1c
msgid ""
"Since the Qubes R3.1 release we have included the Salt (also called "
"SaltStack) management engine in dom0 as default (with some states already"
" configured). Salt allows administrators to easily configure their "
"systems. In this guide we will show how it is set up and how you can "
"modify it for your own purpose."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:11 f990b11c59124f55b05fc70f34526234
msgid ""
"In the current form the **API is provisional** and subject to change "
"between *minor* releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:14 430aba27980f4a3b871ffa52a75738ae
msgid "Understanding Salt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:17 e8e34be45e1c488a8fe18c948ab8fb21
msgid ""
"This document is not meant to be comprehensive Salt documentation; "
"however, before writing anything it is required you have at least *some* "
"understanding of basic Salt-related vocabulary. For more exhaustive "
"documentation, visit `official site "
"<https://docs.saltproject.io/en/latest/>`__, though we must warn you that"
" it is not easy to read if you just start working with Salt and know "
"nothing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:20 7d6f908e09b745dcbe5bd8d51a55a87c
msgid "The Salt Architecture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:23 0bcbae8789414011ba1e926def41e5f1
msgid ""
"Salt is a client-server model, where the server (called *master*) manages"
" its clients (called *minions*). In typical situations, it is intended "
"that the administrator interacts only with the master and keeps the "
"configurations there. In Qubes, we don’t have a master. Instead we have "
"one minion which resides in ``dom0`` and manages qubes from there. This "
"setup is also supported by Salt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:25 025306764b8e4abeb1eb5deb84a26ed2
msgid ""
"Salt is a management engine (similar to Ansible, Puppet, and Chef), that "
"enforces a particular state of a minion system. A *state* is an end "
"effect *declaratively* expressed by the administrator. This is the most "
"important concept in the entire engine. All configurations (i.e., the "
"states) are written in YAML."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:27 e2c387bb882740f6abb7fb6ed551d057
msgid ""
"A *pillar* is a data back-end declared by the administrator. When states "
"become repetitive, instead of pure YAML they can be written using a "
"template engine (preferably Jinja2); which can use data structures "
"specified in pillars."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:29 3b11c11d45424ef5b27a04328a9262c5
msgid ""
"A *formula* is a ready to use, packaged solution that combines a state "
"and a pillar (possibly with some file templates and other auxiliary "
"files). There are many formulas made by helpful people all over the "
"Internet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:31 144c2e61c2174f26881b3dc60d052651
msgid ""
"A *grain* is some data that is also available in templates, but its value"
" is not directly specified by administrator. For example, the "
"distribution (e.g., ``\"Debian\"`` or ``\"Gentoo\"``) is a value of the "
"grain ``\"os\"``. It also contains other information about the kernel, "
"hardware, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:33 c3b8f0ea26bd4271be100e92cab74c3d
msgid ""
"A *module* is a Python extension to Salt that is responsible for actually"
" enforcing the state in a particular area. It exposes some *imperative* "
"functions for the administrator. For example, there is a ``system`` "
"module that has a ``system.halt`` function that, when issued, will "
"immediately halt a domain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:35 61cb433dd3334d2f9ac91798bc410500
msgid ""
"In salt, there are different levels of functionality. The lowest level is"
" a single state function, called like this ``state.single pkg.installed "
"name=firefox-esr`` When the system compiles data from sls formulas, it "
"generates *chunks* - low chunks are at the bottom of the compiler . You "
"can call them with ``state.low``. Next up is the *lowstate* level - this "
"is the list of all low chunks in order. To see them you have "
"``state.show_lowstate``, and use ``state.lowstate`` to apply them. At the"
" top level is *highstate* - this is an interpretation of **all** the data"
" represented in YAML in sls files. You can view it with "
"``state.show_highstate``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:37 1b58c4cd2ecf4af1bc4e2050d5158257
msgid ""
"When you want to apply a configuration, you can use ``qubesctl "
"state.highstate.`` This will apply all the states you have included in "
"highstate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:39 9dd0c6f76bdd48df87e58ad230cab9d0
msgid ""
"There is another function, ``state.apply``; ``state.apply`` has two uses."
" When used on its own, it will apply *highstate* - all the configuration "
"that has been enabled. It can also be used to apply a specific state, "
"like this: ``state.apply browser`` - this will apply the state specified "
"in ``browser.sls``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/advanced-topics/salt.rst:41 93da86be6299487d8a6a5d8f81a48203
msgid ""
"For simplicity we will use ``state.apply`` through this page, when we "
"want to apply all configured states."
msgstr ""

